r the decolonization up to the present day. In the book colonial sources are read from shifting perspectives, of the colonial rulers and, ‘from below’, the ruled. Though leprosy is today a neglected tropical disease, recognizing influences of our colonial heritage in our global management of health and disease, and exploring the perspectives of other cultures are essential in a time in which migration movements make the permeability of boundaries, and transmission of diseases, more common then perhaps ever before.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLeprosyxHistoryxSuriname. 0aLeprosyzSurinamexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh  aAfrican slaves.  aBatavia leprosy asylum.  aCatholics.  aDutch colonial medicine.  aEuropean masters.  aGreat Confinement policies.  aNetherlands.  aProtestants.  aSuriname.  acategories of uncleanliness.  acolonial slave society.  adecolonization.  adetection policies.  aleprosy management.  amodern stigmatization.  asymbiotic alliance.  atreatment policies.  atreef.1 aSnelders, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611301640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526113016423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526113016/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles